wisdom_culture:
wisdom is a human thing, not a culture thing. I dont think they are related. Different cultures use their wisdom is different ways, you could say some cultures are more wise than others, (as in i dont know how wise a primitive tribe could be compared to modern cultures with modern science/research etc. But just because someone is part of a culture with these thing it doesnt make them wise by default.

to clarify, I dont think knowing science etc makes you wise, but i think it encourages people to seek out wisdom. A university student has the time and energy to think about whats right and wrong and how the world works/should work. a member of a primitive tribe is probably more focused on trying to survive. that doesnt mean an indivual tribalist couldnt be wise, but the general culture would not encourage seeking wisdom as much as an other culture could. the other obvious example is religions that support/shun science and individuality

morality_wis_analogy: The history book is to a new generation
moral_wis_comments: Everyone has their own morality, things they believe are acceptable and those that aren't. But as a society, we created general rules of morality - law. We say it is immoral to kill, cheat, rape, steal, and so on. We punish people who do not act according to societal morality. But that common morality changes from culture to culture ever so slightly. And in some circumstances, we forgive and excuse some of those forbidden behaviours because we believe they were justified at the moment they happened, for example in self-defence or to survive. So morality is not set in stone, it is fluctuating with time, cultures and circumstances. Wisdom is what we learned from previous cases, what in the past we called immoral or moral and why. Wisdom is the ability to analyse the rules, and call out those that are outdated, unacceptable, unreasonable, change them and act upon the best judgement at the time. It is not a perfect system, not a steady one, but one that is constantly evolving and changing, not always for the better. It is a process that will never end in an achieved goal of harmony but one that can help us get closer to justice.
wis_psych_char: I don't think it's a straightforward connection. We can perform acts perceived as moral but with having immoral intentions, and the other way around. And it is not always dependent on wisdom. Sometimes people who are wise try to do something good for good reasons but the outcome is negative. It is all relative. I believe, however, that a wise person will try to analyse options, possible outcomes, their own intentions and the needs of others before making a decision that impacts others or the environment. In reality, it is impossible to always remain rational and logical in every decision we make, despite the wisdom we may possess because it is not the only factor that influences our actions or intentions.
wisdom_culture: Every culture has their own wisdom, their own belief system. And in each culture, the wisdom will differ from group to group, family to family, individual to individual. Certain things that are considered moral and acceptable in one culture will be unacceptable in another. The most important question is, how do we decide who is right? And we simply cannot answer that question. But we can use our collective wisdom, learn from the past and conduct research to find out what is the most appropriate approach at the time.

wis_to_moral_agree: Wisdom is relevant for morality,Wisdom is necessary for morality
moral_wis_comments: While morality ultimately drives the decisions people make it is often shaped by their understanding of the environment around them. Animal experiments have shown that there exists an almost moral code wired into the evolution of survival. Animals have exhibited sharing principal when one gets food while the other doesn't. Anthropomorphizing this behaviour can occur but a species could die out if it evolved only to hoard food for the individual. Knowledge can short circuit greed as well as sharing but the motivation for nature drives the survival of the species. One could see this as an inherent moral code or a survival instinct.
wis_psych_char: Empathy seems to be the biggest driver here. Someone with infinite wisdom may be helpful in solving problems but without empathy, you will end up with improper outcomes. The current COVID crisis has been a pretty bleak experiment pitting empathy and wisdom against each other often with undesired outcomes and damage to all participants. A computer could easily choose who lives or dies yet well educated, empathetic, ethical healthcare workers are put in catastrophic positions to make decisions on various outcomes.
wisdom_culture: Wisdom and culture are sometimes parallel but often opposed. Wisdom looks for the best possible result whereas culture often looks for the current majority-supported result. Independent, wise, knowledgeable women in the middle of the last century could either find themselves as a source of help and support for a community or depending on the culture of the area, they could easily be seen as a heretic. The drive to help or nurture could often be seen as a threat to existing patriarchal hierarchies that could eventually undo the wisdom of the matriarchal leader.

consent: I consent to participate in this study
moral_wis_comments:
Morality is created through nurture, the social impact on our opinions/actions will greatly affect what we see as right and wrong moving forward in life. For the most part this is dictated by the dominant religion, regardless of the individuals religious beliefs, as we go through multiple phases in life of trying to fit in with the social dynamic.That dynamic temporarily defines our fashion, entertainment and hobby preferences, but at a more permanent level it defines our morals and ethics -this can be seen in our political opinions when compared to the religious community we grew up in. Even in atheist families its difficult to separate ourselves from religious influences. If we look at gypsy/traveller communities that have very minimal focus on religion on a day-to-day basis, theft and violence is seen as more acceptable based on the morality of providing for and protecting the family/community -from an outsiders viewpoint it is barbaric and many activities should be illegal, but within the community the same acts are seen as a point of pride or for a necessary cause so completely justified.
As far as wisdom in relation to morality, wisdom is the culmination of our life experiences determining how we move forward whereas morality is a preset standard that is supposed to guide us when we have no experience in the matter. Where they crossover is when we experience a moral dilemma and suddenly come to terms with our true beliefs; accept what we have learned from society or defy our lessons in order to do what our gut instinct believes to be correct -wisdom overrides our morality only when our opinion changes due to that defiance. Many grow up being told being gay is a sin, an astonishing amount of antigay politicians and activists have also been revealed as engaging in gay sex/relationships themselves -this shows that wisdom can also be defied by choosing moral principle as infalliable (though it is fair to point out that this could be related to the earlier point of wanting to fit in with our community, even if its only for personal gain, eg not wanting to lose our career).
Just to go back to my analogy; what clothing we wear (individual morality) is based on our surroundings, what cements our fashion choices on a daily basis is first dictated by the weather (life experiences/wisdom) and then what social group we wish to be part of (our nurtured morals/ethics)
wis_psych_char: Our moral intentions/actions are a rough guideline for when we havnt a clue on how we would act instinctively -socially created and supported by research to ensure a positive outcome. Wisdom is how we explain what we've experienced, in most situations it correlates directly to what we thought prior to experiencing the event but it can at times defy our predetermined thoughts
wisdom_culture: Morality is closely tied with culture, wisdom separates itself from morality most often when specifically defying culture in order to make an individual choice

wis_psych_char:
Psychological characteristics shape wisdom almost entirely - The way a person feels can change their moral viewpoint (anger = justice, therefore if I feel angry, my morals shift at that moment).

Furthermore, people judge others on their outcomes and themselves on their intentions, further pushing the idea that it's all subjective to the individual.
wisdom_culture:
Culture absolutely shapes psychological characteristics of wisdom, as some would say that older people are wiser, while others would say they display survivorship bias. 

Furthermore, as cultures shift and innovation and youth are valued (depending on demographics of specific culture), those characteristics and their desirability are changed.

moral_to_wis_agree: Morality is relevant for wisdom,Morality is a precursor for wisdom,Morality is necessary for wisdom
moral_wis_comments: Morality is something we can all try to achieve or pretend to understand it, but wisdom does not happen for everyone. There may be an element of luck to achieving wisdom, i.e. what experiences someone happens to have contribute to their wisdom. But the basic ideas of morality are taught, initially, and through reflection, one develops one's morality. Someone could also just "fake it till they make it" and act as if they understand the morality they are aping. However, I believe the difference between intelligence and wisdom is the effort one puts in to make their morality serve their intelligence.
wis_psych_char: Psychological characteristics of wisdom depend entirely on moral intention, though not so much actions. It may be a Machiavellian way of thinking, but I believe one's actions may not appear to be as in line with one's morality as one's intentions. But without morality behind one's intentions, it isn't wisdom being used, it's cleverness, which may just be serving selfishness or cruelty.
wisdom_culture: I don't believe there is a universal standard of morality, and between different cultures, wisdom might take different forms. What is valued or seen as good in one culture might be entirely unimportant in another, and that informs the way everyone within those cultures would view themselves and others. For example, in one culture, people might view the collective as more important than the individual, which would mean the wisest in that culture would prioritise the needs of a group and view individual needs as not worth considering, whereas in another culture that attitude would be seen as immoral and unwise.

This brings on the interesting debate of wisdom vs culture because those on the outside or those who have gained the wisdom of the hypocrisy of the American Dream moniker know its flaws as a belief while those who choose to believe it, choose to believe that they have the wisdom of the secret to success.

Someone can be wise but not have a system of values or understand a difference between right and wrong in the same way that most of society does. Someone who is declared insane, for example, may have previous experiences/knowledge that makes them incredibly smart. But they may not have the same moral compass that tells them that harming someone is wrong. 
To me, morality is the ability to discern right from wrong.

Their own moral compass tells them that this is a bad thing to do.
wisdom_culture: Wisdom in culture comes down to the experiences that someone obtains from that culture. moral_wis_comments: I think that wisdom can help identify what is right or wrong (if we presume that there are universal rights and wrongs in a Kantian sense), but I don't necessarily think that all people who are wise are moral people, nor do I think that all moral people are wise. wis_psych_char: It really depends on what you mean by wisdom, I suppose. I think that wisdom can pertain to morality, but I think people can also possess wisdom in other domains. In the domain of morality, I do believe that an understanding of both moral intentions and actions is fundamental.
wisdom_culture: Culture inevitably will affect the conceptualization of wisdom. I think culture will likely affect the content, perception, and delivery of wisdom, as well. moral_wis_comments: wisdom, for me, is the innate ability to see things as they truly are and to be able to view the world through multiple different view points and with a fully open mind. To be able to cut through the noise of detail and emotion and bias and be able to observe situations non-judgementally. This ability is critical in order to truly embody other traits such as compassion and empathy and a solid sense of justice - right and wrong - which is where morality comes in.
wis_psych_char: I believe a persons moral intentions and actions are more dependent on their level of wisdom -  as opposed to wisdom being dependant on their moral intentions or actions.
wisdom_culture: I believe culture plays a big part in influencing the psychological characteristic of wisdom.  At the macro level it is clear to me that entire nations that I would say tend to display more wisdom than certain other nations and that this definitely IS as a result of their respective cultures.  Many Asian nations for example are extremely family-oriented and are encouraged from an early age to care for their family members including in to old age and through to death. I believe the people of nations with these types of traditions tend to be more compassionate, naturally wiser and deeper thinking than say, many western countries with cultures that are more centred on material gain, personal success and wealth acquisition where I honestly feel that true wisdom is rarer

wisdom_culture: The only influence culture has on wisdom, in my opinion, is that cultural beliefs influence personal morality to a greater and lesser extent depending on your culture. morality_wis_analogy: understanding issues is to good governance.
moral_wis_comments:
I think the two are closely linked. 

I believe to make a sound moral judgement you need to understand all of the facts within the appropriate context (wisdom).
wis_psych_char:
I believe that people are strongly swayed by their own personal desire regarding a possible outcome, whether they are aware of it or not. 

People who possess wisdom are aware that their own desires affect their understanding of a situation, and can put these inherent biases aside when considering the correct course of action.
wisdom_culture:
There can be a very close relationship between culture and wisdom, depending on the culture and commonly-held beliefs by a population.

If many people are influenced by outside information (i.e. social media), it can form their world-view, whether that view is true or not.

If a culture embraces wisdom shared by experts or those held in high-regard, and based on fact, not feelings, the culture itself will be truth-driven, and not held hostage to views driven by emotion or inherent biases.

moral_wis_comments:
In terms of the multiverse, there is no such thing as morality. We are insignificant beings in the grand scale of things. Morality is an evolutionary utility to ensure the propagation of the human race.

that being said, morality can be gained from wisdom, but not necessarily wisdom from morality. It could be said that morality is a form of wisdom regarding common tacit terms of coexistence
wisdom_culture: there are many forms of wisdom. Sometimes they can overlap and have co-relation. Culture is the continual evolution of human societal structure. The human brain has been pushed to its impressive capacity as we see today in a great degree by the development culture, pushed so much so that some parts of the brain have regressed in order to cater for the changing evolutionary priority of cognitive resources. Advancement of cultural understanding and capability does not necessarily coincide with wisdom. Often in fact individuals that navigate culture to their great advantage are for all essential purposes dumb, and just a lucky Zeitgeist product.

morality_wis_analogy: A hand is to a finger
moral_wis_comments: Morality feeds wisdom, but wisdom can exist in the absence of morality. While morality is a subjective categorization of a variable spectrum of choices, wisdom is the culmination of the ability of a person to discern past the initial binary of right and wrong to see further into the variability of a particular moral situation. While this is not the only aspect of wisdom, and is certainly not necessary for the attainment of wisdom as I would define it, it can lead to further development of personal wisdom.
wis_psych_char: Wisdom depends on congruity of intentions and actions regardless of moral associations with these actions. Attaching morality to the amoral state of wisdom pre-colors perception of the actions to a viewer who cannot have known the original intentions of the actor. This preconception in the mind of the viewer then abstracts the intention from the action, where in the mind of the wise actor, these two are the same.
wisdom_culture: Culture feeds perceptions of wisdom. Culture creates a series of signs by which the wisdom of an individual can be judged.

moral_to_wis_agree: Morality is relevant for wisdom,Morality is a precursor for wisdom,Morality is necessary for wisdom
moral_wis_comments: I see wisdom as permanent and morality as temporary. That is because morality can change over time (ie. what is right or wrong for me today may be different in the future). On the other hand, wisdom is more permanent. It may differ between cultures but in a given population or individual, wisdom remains permanent. We learn through experiences/actions and we gain wisdom every time and it sticks with us for future experiences (ie. good judgment).
wisdom_culture: In my opinion, the psychological characteristics of wisdom differs in between cultures. Every culture (western vs non-westen) has their difference in their past and philosophies. Some cultures may believe that it is the reasoning ability, empathy (amongst others) that are the focus, while others may believe wisdom is more the notion of maturity. In other words, I believe that wisdom is malleable from one culture to another.

moral_wis_comments:
If going by the Oxford dictionary definition of wisdom as 'the ability to make sensible decisions and give good advice because of the experience and knowledge' I believe wisdom can exist without morality. 
For example, a serial killer or genocidal tyrant would be considered lacking in morality, but they may still possess abilities (through experience and knowledge) that make them wise within their individual arenas.
wis_psych_char:
Religious and cultural beliefs vastly affect a persons interpretation of morality. For example, fundamentally religious people of both Christianity & Islam will openly condemn people of a different sexual persuasion. This would be in contrast to the generalist view of such behavior being immoral.  

Intelligence, or lack thereof, certainly holds sway on the individuals abilities to discern from right and wrong.
wisdom_culture: As before.

moral_to_wis_agree: Morality is relevant for wisdom,Morality is a precursor for wisdom,Morality is necessary for wisdom
moral_wis_comments: I think of morality as our application of individual and societal values to determine right from wrong. I think of wisdom as something we gain from reflecting on our lived experience, including our application of morality. I do not think a person can be both amoral and wise. I have encountered many moral people who were not wise.

morality_wis_analogy: Science is to spirituality. Each has its own uses and when you try to make one work as a function of the other you get a world of problems.
moral_wis_comments:
A toddler has little wisdom but is able to understand morality (be dressed in front of others, do not swear, respect your elders).

A wise person may choose to ignore morality and still be wise (such as breaking taboo to save a life).

Wisdom is as separate from morality as morality is from ethics.
wis_psych_char: Wisdom does not depend on morality. The illusion of wisdom stemming from morality can actually cause a person to take unwise action, unconnected to the morality of their intentions.
wisdom_culture:
Cultures evolve much like living beings. Popular wisdom is wisdom that has, at least up to the present, survived the test of time.

For example: popular wisdom might dictate that a certain plant or animal must be avoided. Regardless of the scientific understand about such plant or animal, if at some point it would be a vector of disease or addiction, then the wisdom was right. Such wisdom then gets committed to culture where it can persist for generations until it is discarded by newer wisdom; And as long as it is passed from generation to generation, it will be imprinted in the psyche of the people.

moral_wis_comments:
I don't think so. 

Morality, at its most basic, is an idea of whats right and wrong.
wis_psych_char:
I think that the psychological characteristics of wisdom DO depend on moral intentions or actions, quite a lot. 
Moral intentions or actions are usually determined by the cultural norm, so it makes sense the idea of wisdom is built around that.
wisdom_culture:
I think there is a relationship. Cultures have created their own social norms, which can vary differently, and these norms inform our ideas of wisdom. 

For example, in one culture it might be deemed wise to leave babies to sleep outside, as it aids their sleeping and has many health benefits. In another culture it is deemed wise to never leave your babies to sleep outside to protect them from strangers and any possible danger.

moral_wis_comments:
I think you can be wise without being moral and you can be moral without being wise. Obviously there can be cross over and there may even be correlation but for me the first two statements are fundamental.

I understand morality to be a spectrum of 'perceived good and bad' on which a person sits and bases their various decisions on how to interact with the world around them.
wisdom_culture: I think culture and wisdom are more intertwined than wisdom and morality. If there is a culture of introspection, respect, communication, evolution, that would lay out a natural path for individuals to become wise. If a culture is violent, insulated, stifles communication then the organic product would surely be a less accessible path to wisdom? Although even in the latter culture there would be wise individuals it might be harder for them to impart wisdom.

morality_wis_analogy: Literacy is to the ability to communicate with others
moral_wis_comments: I think that it would be difficult to be a moral person without wisdom.  When I speak of wisdom, I'm not talking of education, but rather an understanding of how the treatment of others affects them and their subsequent feelings and decisions.  It's also an understanding about the interconnectedness of everything; people, animals, plants, the environment both natural and built.  How could you make moral judgments, without a sense of why something would be right or wrong?
wis_psych_char: I think that moral intentions - the desire to either do the right thing or not - certainly affects wisdom.  If someone doesn't care whether or not their actions harm others, they're not going to bother to observe the result of their actions other than how their actions affect themselves and their desires.  You cannot gain wisdom without observation.
wisdom_culture: I think that culture can affect wisdom, in that some cultures can contribute to people's sense of self worth either positively or negatively (eg some cultures devalue women, others frown on homosexuality).  If a person is brought up to believe that their opinions have no value, they are less likely to develop a sense of curiosity about the world around them.  Without that sense of curiosity they are unlikely to gain wisdom.

morality_wis_analogy: engine is to fuel. An engine (wisdom) needs fuel (morality) to run.
moral_wis_comments:
I think wisdom as an electric engine of an electric car.
Electricity is morality (the fuel). It gives the necessary energy to run the engine (wisdom). At the same time every time the driver hits the brakes, the heat energy produced is stored as electricity in the battery, offering some more energy to the car.
Morality feeds wisdom, but at the same time, in a well designed and properly running system, wisdom will feed back morality just a bit, making morality more efficient.
wis_psych_char:
Moral intentions and actions determine the psychological characteristics of wisdom.
If someone gets Covid their morality will determine how they will behave towards others and how they will deal personally with the fact.
Morality will remind the Covid-affected their obligation to protect others and state their situation to their social circle, not only because some law dictates it, but because their dealing of the illness will affect the lives of others.
Morality will be the base which will determine what the ill person's contemplation of their situation will bring forth, how that person will deal with the prospect of long lasting symptoms or even the death.
